{"parse":{"title":"Berta languages","pageid":21772188,"revid":834048954,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox\" style=\"width:22em;width:22em;\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold;background-color: gold;\">Berta</th></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Geographic<br />distribution</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Ethiopia\" title=\"Ethiopia\">Ethiopia</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Sudan\" title=\"Sudan\">Sudan</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\"><a href=\"/wiki/Language_family\" title=\"Language family\">Linguistic classification</a></th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Nilo-Saharan_languages\" title=\"Nilo-Saharan languages\">Nilo-Saharan</a>?<ul style=\"line-height:100%; margin-left:15px;padding-left:0\"><li><b>Berta</b></li></ul></td></tr><tr class=\"plainlist\"><th scope=\"row\">Subdivisions</th><td>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Berta_language\" title=\"Berta language\">Gebeto</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Fadashi_language\" title=\"Fadashi language\">Fadashi</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Undu_language\" title=\"Undu language\">Undu</a></li></ul>\n</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\"><a href=\"/wiki/ISO_639-3\" title=\"ISO 639-3\">ISO 639-3</a></th><td>\n<tt><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www-01.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=wti\">wti</a></tt></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\"><a href=\"/wiki/Glottolog\" title=\"Glottolog\">Glottolog</a></th><td>\n<samp><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://glottolog.org/resource/languoid/id/bert1248\">bert1248</a></samp><sup id=\"cite_ref-Glottolog_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Glottolog-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p>The <b>Berta languages</b>, or <b>Wetawit</b>, traditionally considered dialects of a single language, are <a href=\"/wiki/Berta_language\" title=\"Berta language\">Gebeto</a> (Berta proper), <a href=\"/wiki/Fadashi_language\" title=\"Fadashi language\">Fadashi</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Undu_language\" title=\"Undu language\">Undu</a>. They are either a small family (or <a href=\"/wiki/Language_isolate\" title=\"Language isolate\">language isolate</a>) of their own, or a primary branch of the <a href=\"/wiki/Nilo-Saharan\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Nilo-Saharan\">Nilo-Saharan</a> language family.\n</p><p>Berta has the typical word order <a href=\"/wiki/Subject%E2%80%93verb%E2%80%93object\" title=\"Subject\u2013verb\u2013object\">subject\u2013verb\u2013object</a>.  It is a <a href=\"/wiki/Tone_(linguistics)\" title=\"Tone (linguistics)\">tonal</a> language.  It has significantly influenced some of the <a href=\"/wiki/Eastern_Jebel_languages\" title=\"Eastern Jebel languages\">Eastern Jebel languages</a>.  The Arabic name \"Beni-Shangul\" (as in the Ethiopian province of <a href=\"/wiki/Benishangul-Gumuz\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Benishangul-Gumuz\">Benishangul-Gumuz</a>) derives from a Berta expression (with <i>bele</i> \"rock/stone\" misanalyzed as Arabic <i>beni</i> \"sons\").\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Berta_languages&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Glottolog-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Glottolog_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Hammarstr\u00f6m, Harald; Forkel, Robert; Haspelmath, Martin, eds. (2017). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://glottolog.org/resource/languoid/id/bert1248\">\"Berta\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/Glottolog\" title=\"Glottolog\">Glottolog 3.0</a></i>. Jena, Germany: Max Planck Institute for the Science of Human History.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Berta&amp;rft.btitle=Glottolog+3.0&amp;rft.place=Jena%2C+Germany&amp;rft.pub=Max+Planck+Institute+for+the+Science+of+Human+History&amp;rft.date=2017&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fglottolog.org%2Fresource%2Flanguoid%2Fid%2Fbert1248&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABerta+languages\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<style data-mw-deduplicate=\"TemplateStyles:r853264625\">.mw-parser-output .refbegin{font-size:90%;margin-bottom:0.5em}.mw-parser-output .refbegin-hanging-indents>ul{list-style-type:none;margin-left:0}.mw-parser-output .refbegin-hanging-indents>ul>li,.mw-parser-output .refbegin-hanging-indents>dl>dd{margin-left:0;padding-left:3.2em;text-indent:-3.2em;list-style:none}.mw-parser-output .refbegin-100{font-size:100%}</style><div class=\"refbegin\" style=\"\">\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.rogerblench.info/Language/Nilo-Saharan/General/NS%20language%20list.pdf\">Roger Blench</a></li></ul>\n</div>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><i>This <a href=\"/wiki/Nilo-Saharan_languages\" title=\"Nilo-Saharan languages\">Nilo-Saharan languages</a>-related article is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help Wikipedia by <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Berta_languages&amp;action=edit\">expanding it</a>.</i><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\" style=\"position: absolute; right: 15px; display: none;\"><ul><li class=\"nv-view\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template:NiloSaharan-lang-stub\" title=\"Template:NiloSaharan-lang-stub\"><abbr title=\"View this template\">v</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-talk\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template_talk:NiloSaharan-lang-stub\" title=\"Template talk